# RageForge addon — conventions

RageForge is a WoW Classic Anniversary (TBC content) addon written in Lua.
It targets warrior PvP and helps with stance-dance rage economy.

## Target client

- **Client folder:** `_anniversary_`
- **Interface number:** `20505` (TBC Anniversary, v2.5.5, as of 2026)
- **Install path:**
  `C:\Program Files (x86)\World of Warcraft\_anniversary_\Interface\AddOns\RageForge\`
- Per-client TOC suffixes are not used; we ship a single `RageForge.toc`.
- If a patch bumps the Interface number, update `RageForge.toc` first.

## Project layout

```
rageforge/
  RageForge/             addon folder; this is what gets copied into AddOns
    RageForge.toc        manifest, file load order
    Config.lua           SavedVariables, defaults, /rf slash command
    Core.lua             event router + OnUpdate driver, no display logic
    RageBar.lua          curved bar, zones, ghost line, ticks, cap glow
    Options.lua          standalone /rf options settings window + optional AddOns registration
    Fonts/Prototype.ttf  bundled font for bar UI (with Prototype.txt readme)
  install.ps1            PowerShell copy / junction script
  package.ps1            builds clean release zip in dist/
  CHANGELOG.md           user-facing release notes
  LICENSE                MIT license
  README.md
  .cursor/rules/         IDE rules (this file)
```

**Load order matters.** Config must load first (provides `ns.Config.db`),
then Core (init), then RageBar (assumes Config is ready),
then Options (which reads `ns.Config.db` and writes back through it).

## Lua / WoW API conventions

- All modules attach to the addon namespace: `local _, ns = ...; ns.X = {}`.
  Never pollute globals beyond the unavoidable `RageForgeDB` SavedVar and
  `SLASH_RAGEFORGE*` slash registrations.
- Use `CreateFrame("Frame", ...)` for event handling; one frame per concern
  is fine, but Core owns the main event router.
- For rage: power type id is `1` (or `Enum.PowerType.Rage` if available).
- For combat log parsing use `CombatLogGetCurrentEventInfo()`. The first 11
  fields are always: `timestamp, subevent, hideCaster, sourceGUID, sourceName,
  sourceFlags, sourceRaidFlags, destGUID, destName, destFlags, destRaidFlags`.
  After that, payload depends on subevent:
  - `SWING_*`: damage/miss params start at field 12.
  - `SPELL_*`: `spellId, spellName, spellSchool` at 12-14, then payload.
- Avoid per-frame allocations in `OnUpdate` (no table literals, no captures
  in tight loops). The current OnFrame paths are allocation-free; keep it
  that way.

## Stance-dance math (the linchpin)

Tactical Mastery in TBC retains 5 rage per rank, max 25 at 5/5. On stance
change rage drops to `min(currentRage, retainedRage)`. The user-configurable
value `cfg.tacticalMasteryRetained` is the single source of truth — every
visual decision (zones, ghost line, number color) routes through it.

**Never** hardcode `25`. Always read `ns.Config.db.tacticalMasteryRetained`.

## Visual conventions

- Zones (`cfg.zones`) are flat RGBA tables, not Color objects. `RageBar.lua`
  blends between zone stops by returning raw `r,g,b,a` values; do not allocate
  color tables per row/frame. Current palette is brighter than v0.5 but still
  warrior-flavored: emerald -> bright gold -> molten orange -> blood red.
- The bar is rendered as a **stack of 1-pixel horizontal rows**. Each row has
  an opaque center `Texture` plus lower-alpha left/right feather textures.
  Row centers are pixel-snapped (`snapPixel`) to reduce texture sampling
  shimmer; feather strips soften the staircase edge. We tried `CreateLine`
  chains in v0.3-0.4; chained thick lines do not seam cleanly because the
  thickness is perpendicular to the line direction (so on slopes, lines become
  visibly narrower than peers, producing horizontal stripes). Don't go back.
  If the user wants a perfect bend, create custom TGA/BLP art in
  `RageForge/Textures/` and reference it as
  `Interface\\AddOns\\RageForge\\Textures\\<name>`.
- Bar UI text uses bundled `Interface\\AddOns\\RageForge\\Fonts\\Prototype.ttf`
  with `Fonts\\SKURRI.TTF` fallback through `setFont()` in RageBar.lua. New
  RageBar text should call `setFont(fs, size, flags)` rather than `SetFont`
  directly. The release zip must always include `Prototype.txt` next to the
  font file because the font's own readme asks for that when redistributing.
- **Nothing crosses the bar except the bar itself.** Ticks stay outside the
  bar to the right. Ghost-line + dump-hint live outside the bar to the left.
  Anchor ticks against `_barCenterlineX + xOff + barWidth/2`; anchor ghost
  hints against `_barCenterlineX + xOff - barWidth/2`.
- The ghost-line family (notch + line + dump-hint label) only shows when
  `currentRage > retainedRage`. Below that, hide all three -- no decision to
  make so no UI to draw.
- No Overpower overlay/module. It was removed in v0.8 after user feedback.
  Do not re-add combat-log dodge parsing, green rim glows, `/rf op`, or
  `/rf test` unless the user explicitly asks for it again.
- Fill rendering must keep each filled row center fully opaque. `Render()`
  rounds `displayedRage` to the nearest whole rage before coloring slices so
  the current-rage row never appears as a faded partial band. Only edge
  feathers use reduced alpha.
- Stance icons live in `stanceArtifacts`. They are square-cropped and rotated
  via 8-argument `SetTexCoord` so each spell icon's top edge points left and
  its bottom edge visually touches the bar. Keep them packed as a tight stack
  (`stanceIconSize` spacing), with right edges snapped to the bar's left edge.
  Do not tint/desaturate them; active stance may be alpha 1.0 and inactive
  stances alpha-dimmed only. Active stance also shows
  `Interface\\Buttons\\UI-ActionButton-Border` as a gold outline; don't tint
  the icon itself. Classic can crop/rotate rectangular textures, but it cannot
  truly mask arbitrary stance icons into a curved silhouette without custom
  art. If the user wants a perfect bent/cropped strip, create custom TGA art in
  `RageForge/Textures/` rather than trying to fake masks with frame layers.
- Battle Shout reminder lives in RageBar.lua (`battleShoutFrame`). It shows
  only for warriors when Battle Shout is missing or has <=
  `cfg.battleShoutWarnSeconds` remaining. `UNIT_AURA` updates it immediately,
  and `OnFrame` performs a 1-second aura refresh so the icon starts flashing
  when a healthy buff naturally crosses the 30-second threshold. Detection is
  intentionally tolerant of Classic aura return differences: compare by name,
  substring, and icon path, and treat `expirationTime` as either an absolute
  timestamp or remaining seconds. If remaining time exists, show it on
  `battleShoutTimerFS`. Some clients expose only `duration`; in that case,
  `UNIT_SPELLCAST_SUCCEEDED` and `battleShoutDurationStartedAt` provide a
  local countdown so the reminder can still appear at <=30s. On successful
  Battle Shout cast, hide the icon immediately and prefer the local countdown
  over stale aura remaining time so reapplying the buff clears the warning.
  Suppress it while `UnitIsDeadOrGhost("player")`.
- **No background box, ever.** v0.1 had a translucent black panel, v0.2-0.4
  had a faint blue `bgHandle` shown only when unlocked. Both got user
  pushback. Drag affordance now lives in the `RAGE` label (text changes
  to "RAGE \194\183 drag" in light blue when unlocked). Don't reintroduce
  bg art.

## Schema migrations (Config.lua)

`fillDefaults` only fills *missing* keys. When you change the *value* of an
existing default in a way that should propagate to existing users (e.g. a
recolor), bump `C.SCHEMA_VERSION` and add a migration block in `C:Load`
that hard-replaces the affected keys via `resetTo`. Otherwise users who
already have a `RageForgeDB.lua` will be stuck on the old values forever.
This also applies to array-like defaults such as `thresholdTicks`; adding a
new tick value needs a schema migration because `fillDefaults` will not append
new numeric indices to an existing saved table.

## Slash commands

User-facing: `/rf` and `/rf help`. When adding new commands, update both
`Config.lua handleSlash` and the help block in the same function. Keep flags
short and mnemonic.

## Options panel (Options.lua)

- `/rf` and `/rf options` open RageForge's own standalone movable window. This is the
  reliable settings path. We may still call legacy `InterfaceOptions_AddCategory`
  when available, but do not depend on the Blizzard AddOns list surfacing the
  category on Anniversary clients.
- Anniversary 2.5.5 does **not** have the modern Dragonflight
  `Settings.RegisterAddOnCategory` API. Don't use it.
- All controls write directly to `ns.Config.db` and call `RageBar:ApplyConfig()`
  on change for live preview. No Apply button.
- The settings window includes creator bio/social links. Keep them compact and
  informational; WoW Classic cannot reliably open external URLs, so display
  copyable/plain text rather than trying to launch a browser.
- `panel.default` deep-copies `ns.Config.defaults` back into `ns.Config.db`
  and calls `panel.refresh()`. The Blizzard Defaults button is the supported
  reset path.
- Lua 5.1 in WoW does NOT support `\u{XXXX}` escapes (added in 5.3). Encode
  multibyte glyphs as raw UTF-8 byte escapes (e.g. middle dot \194\183, em-dash
  \226\128\148) or stick to ASCII.
- New settings? Add a default to `Config.defaults`, expose a control in
  `Options:Build()`, and (if it changes bar geometry) note that a /reload is
  required.

## Testing without WoW

You can't run WoW Lua outside the client, so:

- After significant changes, install with `.\install.ps1 -Symlink` once and
  use `/reload` in game to test live.
- For rage-bar changes you can adjust `cfg.tacticalMasteryRetained` and
  visually inspect ghost line / zone transitions while standing still.

## Publishing

- GitHub repo should be public as `SommerChase/rageforge`.
- Use `package.ps1` for CurseForge/GitHub release zips. The archive must contain
  a top-level `RageForge/` folder, not loose addon files.
- Keep `LICENSE`, `CHANGELOG.md`, and README social/bio section current.
- The release zip and the GitHub repo bundle `RageForge/Fonts/Prototype.ttf`
  together with `RageForge/Fonts/Prototype.txt`. The `.txt` file is the font
  author's readme and is required for redistribution. Never ship the .ttf
  without the .txt.

## Style

- Keep comments to *why* / *invariants*, not narration. The team reads code
  for what it does; comments earn their place by encoding intent or warning.
- No emoji in code or chat output. Print prefix is the addon name in red.
- Function names are PascalCase for module methods (`Bar:Update`), camelCase
  for locals.
- Two-space indent? **No** — keep four-space, that's the Blizzard / Classic
  addon norm and matches existing files.

## Known gotchas

- Anniversary client may show "Out of Date" if Blizzard bumps the Interface
  number mid-phase. Tell the user to either toggle the AddOns screen option
  or bump `## Interface:` in the TOC.
- Frame anchor strata: don't use `BACKGROUND` for anything that should be
  visible above world UI; `ARTWORK`/`OVERLAY` are correct for the bar.
- `RegisterEvent("UNIT_POWER_UPDATE")` payload is `(unit, "RAGE")` — string,
  not numeric power type.
